Image classification using CNNs in Keras - Weed vs Crop¶

Domain:¶

Agriculture

Context:¶

Can you differentiate a weed from a crop seedling? The ability to do so effectively can mean better crop yields and better stewardship of the environment. The Aarhus University Signal Processing group, in collaboration with University of Southern Denmark, has recently released a dataset containing images of approximately 960 unique plants belonging to 12 species at several growth stages.

Data Description:¶

We are provided with a dataset of images of plant seedlings at various stages of grown. Each image has a filename that is its unique id. The dataset comprises 12 plant species. The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo. The list of species is as follows:

  • Black-grass
  • Charlock
  • Cleavers
  • Common Chickweed
  • Common wheat
  • Fat Hen
  • Loose Silky-bent
  • Maize
  • Scentless Mayweed
  • Shepherds Purse
  • Small-flowered Cranesbill
  • Sugar beet

File descriptions

  • images.npy
  • Label.csv

Goal:¶

The goal of the project is to create a classifier capable of determining a plant's species from a photo.

Steps and tasks¶

  1. Import the libraries, load dataset, print shape of data, visualize the images in dataset.
  2. Data Pre-processing
  3. Make data compatible
  4. Building CNN
  5. Fit and evaluate model and print confusion matrix
  6. Visualize predictions
  7. Summary

def plot_counts_percentages(array):
    total_greens = array.shape[0]
    names, counts = np.unique(labels, return_counts = True)
    idxs = counts.argsort()
    order=names[idxs[::-1]]
    chart = sns.countplot(x=array, palette='muted', order=order);
    chart.set(xlabel='', ylabel='Count')
    chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(),  rotation=90)
    for p in chart.patches:
        height = p.get_height()
        chart.text(p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2., height + 3, '{:1.2f}'.format((height/total_greens)*100), ha='center')

Visualize the images¶

In [8]:
def cv2_imshow(ocv_img, title=''):
    h, w = ocv_img.shape[:2]
    h = (h % 100) /5
    w = (w % 100) /5
    plt.figure(figsize=(h,w))
    # When the image file is read with the OpenCV function imread(), the order of colors is BGR,
    # to display it with matplotlib we want to convert it to RGB
    img = cv2.cvtColor(ocv_img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB);
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    if title:
        plt.title(title)
    plt.imshow(img)
    plt.show()
In [9]:
def show_select_2x3(imgs, labels, indices):
    rows = 2
    cols = 3
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))

    for idx, index in enumerate(indices):
        plt.subplot(rows, cols, idx+1)
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])
        plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(imgs[index], cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
        plt.title(labels[index])

    plt.show()

2. Data Pre-processing¶

Gaussian blurring¶

We want our images to be less noisy. We can achieve that by applying a low pass filter which will smooth the image.

Gaussian Blurring is a widely used technique in graphics software, typically to reduce image noise and reduce detail. It is also used as a preprocessing stage before applying machine learning algorithms or deep learning models. We need to specify the width and height of the kernel which should be positive and odd. Also the standard deviation in the X and Y directions, sigmaX and sigmaY respectively. If only sigmaX is specified, sigmaY is taken as equal to sigmaX.

In [13]:
img_gauss = [None] * images.shape[0]
for index, img in enumerate(images):
    img_gauss[index] = cv2.GaussianBlur(img, (5, 5), 2)
img_gauss = np.array(img_gauss)

Normalize data¶

We need to normalize our data as it is always required in neural network models. We can achieve this by dividing the RGB codes by 255 (which is the maximum RGB code minus the minimum RGB code). Important that the values are float so that we can get decimal points after division.

In [14]:
img_norm_gauss = img_gauss.astype('float32') / 255

Split the dataset into training, testing, and validation set.¶

Keras is perfectly capable of doing validation_split itself, however, we are required to do it manually by the project describtion. So first we split our pre-processed images and labels into training and testing set with using ratio = 0.3. And then we split testing set into new testing and validation sets with ratio = 0.5 Let's do it now.

In [19]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
seed=33

# split dataset into training and test set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(img_norm_gauss, label_one_hot_vectors,  test_size=0.30, random_state=seed)

# split testing set into new testing  and validation sets
X_test, X_valid, y_test, y_valid = train_test_split(X_test, y_test, test_size=0.5, random_state=seed)

Insights:

  • As we can see from the training history accuracy metric and loss are quick to overfit, starting around epoch 3-4.
  • Although accuracy of 0.75 on the testing set can be considered good, we have pretty heigh loss.

Points of Improvement:

  • As our model is overfitting we will add Dropout layers for the regularization.
  • Also since evry convolution layer changes the data in a way that does not guarantee normalization, we will add BatchNormalization layers after each of them.
  • Let us leave as much useful information as we can, let us include the edges in the training process too.
  • Further we have the learning rate for Adam optimizer which defaults to 0.001. Let us give it a smaller rate and help it automatically decrease if it reaches stagnation. As we are decreasing the learning rate we expect the training to take longer time and so we will increase the number of epochs too and at the same time we provide an early exit if we see that our loss stopped improving.
  • To finish our proposals off, we probably want to save & use the best weights that we encountered during the training, we will define our best weights at the best loss.

Best attempt¶

Now let us present our best attempt at the model configuration.

Define layers¶

In [55]:
classifier = models.Sequential()

classifier.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (5, 5), padding='same', activation="relu", input_shape=X_train.shape[1:]))
classifier.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
classifier.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
classifier.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (5, 5), padding='same', activation="relu"))
classifier.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
classifier.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
classifier.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation="relu"))
classifier.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
classifier.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
classifier.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), padding='same', activation="relu"))
classifier.add(layers.BatchNormalization())
classifier.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
classifier.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))

classifier.add(layers.Flatten())
classifier.add(layers.Dense(256, activation="relu"))
classifier.add(layers.Dropout(0.5))
classifier.add(layers.Dense(12, activation="softmax"))

classifier.summary()

Insights:

  • After several experiments the above model showed the best results. Here we decided to go with a few pairs of Conv2D and MaxPooling2D layers. Also since there is no guarantee that all the values a properly scaled after a convolution layer we use BatchNormalization layers to remedy that. We also have couple of Dropout layers for the regularization purposes. Before passing the results to the dense neural network we reshape the data into the appropriate 1D vector format.
  • Also in this CNN we choose not to loose any information on the edges and so we always add the relative padding.

Set optimizer and loss function¶

Per project description we need to use Adam optimizer, we set loss function to categorical crossentropy as it is a logical choice for our problem.

In [56]:
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)

early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', min_delta=0.001, patience=3)
checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath='./checkpoint_filepath', monitor='val_loss', verbose=1, save_best_only=True, save_weights_only=True, mode='auto')
reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.5, patience=1, verbose=1, mode='auto', min_lr=0.000001)

classifier.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])

Insights:

  • One of the improvements worth noticing is the introduction of the ReduceLROnPlateau callback. To help our model to recover from learning stagnation, we introduce this callback with the validation loss metric and patience set to 1 epoch.
  • Also we will keep the best weights our model encountered during the training at lowes loss & provide an early exit.

In [61]:
plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Training')
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation')
plt.title('Loss History')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Insights:

  • We reached a pretty good accuracy of ~0.86 on our testing set. We had a good reduction in loss up until ~epoch 10, our loss is 0.44 on the testing set.
  • Our ReduceLROnPlateau callback helped us to reduce learing rate several times when the loss stoped improving and it helped our model to recover. Also as we can see further reduction of the learning rate beyond 1e-06 did not help.
  • Our EarlyStopping call back helped us to stop (epoch 26) when loss stoped descreasing.
  • Finally our ModelCheckpoint allowed us to save the best weights.

  • No overfitting.

  • Overall we significantly improved over our elier models, we reduced loss twice and improved accuracy from 0.75 to 0.86.

In [68]:
def show_pred_2x3(imgs, labels_true, labels_pred, indices):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))

    for idx, index in enumerate(indices):
        plt.subplot(2, 3, idx+1)
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])
        plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(imgs[index], cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
        plt.title(f'Index: {index}\nTrue: {labels_true[index]}\nPred: {labels_pred[index]}')

    plt.show()
In [69]:
show_pred_2x3(X_test, y_test_labels, y_pred_labels, [2, 3, 33, 36, 59])

Insights:

  • All samples predicted correctly.

7. Summary¶

Overall we were able to build a good claciffier capable of determining plant's species from a photo and accuracy of ~86%. We used CNN and employed several callback techniques to improve model's performance. Image pre-processing also helped our classifier to achive better results.

It is worth notting that further improvement of the model is possible. We may balance the dataset and applying some more sophisticated image preprocessing techniques. Also, it is well known that for the classification purposes we don't need color images, we could have actually converted them to grayscale and so, at the very least, reduced the number of parameters to be learned by our CNN.
